    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-02T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-02T18:00:00-05:00" n="725"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d725">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6901: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-02T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 2, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>396. Your 1051, June 1, 6 p.m., last paragraph. The Department desires that,
                    unless you perceive objection, you strongly urge the appropriate French
                    authorities to facilitate by all reasonable methods the transit of the tung oil
                    shipments, basing your approach on (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) the need of the
                    American paint industry for the tung oil, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) the fact
                    that the shipments of tung oil are the means for repayment for the $25,000,000
                    credit extended by the Export-Import Bank,<note n="64" xml:id="d725fn64">For
                        further correspondence, see <ref target="#pg_636">pp. 636</ref> ff.</note>
                    and (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) the fact that delivery of the tung oil will
                    operate toward maintaining China’s credit which in turn is to the interest of
                    all countries desirous of maintaining normal and healthy relations with
                    China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
